Appropriation/Budget Activity                                                                R-1 Program E$$, $$cd4ec4534fa5ac3d42e5ae6cba4fcf00987ae16501a83c758545a87b914441e9$$, $${"A": "c12065b198bdac589879d0980ee9fa7e873b582d941e142a3f76301e93482533", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "a77b4d1307a0d0591a95a11940bb4a8477fbb8f40934531a22cbc77bc7307ea8"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Air Force/FY27 Air Force Research, Development, Test & Evaluation  Volume III.pdf$$, 589, $$2026-05-10T04:04:15.272057+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$1206447SF$$, 2027, $$The program office is developing and prototyping the Resilient Missile Warning Tracking (MWT) MEO (Project 657MEO) for Guardians across Missile Warning and
Missile Tracking (MW/MT) mission area. As a result, the Service will advance space-based technology associated with Golden Dome, and deter, neutralize, defeat and/
or destroy counterspace threats and defend the homeland.

 A new class of threat requires a new class of architecture. Since legacy systems alone cannot maintain custody of advanced, dim and maneuverable missile threats,
 Resilient MWT delivers a multi-orbit architecture designed to defeat new threats, support homeland defense, Combatant Command operations and the broader missile
 defense kill chain. The United States Space Force Space Systems Command and Space Development Agency are collaborating to deliver Overhead Persistent
 Infrared capabilities, in concert with Department of War and Intelligence Community partners, to support a proliferated space architecture that is resilient by design and
 capable of operating through contested environments. Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking - Medium Earth Orbit space and ground efforts pivot the Department
 of the Air Force's legacy missile warning force design to a more resilient multi-orbit approach to counter advanced missiles, hypersonic glide vehicles, and fractional
 orbital bombardment threats. Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking Medium Earth Orbit was originally anchored in Missile Warning and Missile Defense Capability
 Development Document requirements validated by the Joint Requirements Oversight Council; there is now a Joint Requirement Oversight Council-approved Capability
 Development Document Annex with very specific Medium Earth Orbit and Low Earth Orbit requirements. Constellation resiliency is foundational to the Department of the
 Air Force's Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking force design, therefore, the Overhead Persistent Infrared Family of Systems, including Missile Warning and Tracking
 Medium Earth Orbit, is designed to work cohesively to gain and maintain custody of a spectrum of missile threats.

 This program falls within the Missile Warning and Missile Tracking (MW/MT) mission area which provides the multi-orbit space and ground architecture required to detect
 and track missiles and hypersonic glide vehicles worldwide. Space Force investment program interdependencies include:
 RDT&E Budget Line Items: Missile Defense Radars (1203873SF); Ballistic Missile EW Systems (1203909SF); Joint Tactical Ground System (1208053SF); NCMC - TW/
 AA System (1203906SF); Next - Generation OPIR (1206442SF); Next - Generation - GEO (1206443SF); Next - Generation - Ground (1206440SF); Next - Generation
 - Polar (1206444SF); NUDET Detection System (1203913SF); Resilient MW / MT - LEO (1206446SF); Resilient MW / MT - MEO (1206447SF) and elements of
 Procurement Budget Line Item: Space Mods (SPCMOD).

 The Medium Earth Orbit program will deploy space assets in multiple Epochs to allow for incremental capability delivery and to ensure competition throughout the
 lifecycle of the program. Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking Medium Earth Orbit will bolster legacy Space Based Infrared Satellite and Next-Gen Overhead
 Persistent Infrared capabilities and will independently satisfy mission area Capability Development Document requirements for missile tracking by as early as FY

 2033. FY 2026 funding supports final build, test, and delivery of flight payloads and buses to support Epoch 1, space vehicle level assembly integration and test, and
 launch/early orbit operations. FY 2026 funding also includes ground activities previously captured in PE 1206448SF, Project 657124, that continue ground segment
 Mission Data Processing application development and integration, command and control software and facilities build and integration into the Medium Earth Orbit Space
 Operations Center, and ground entry point site construction to support on-orbit initialization in FY 2027. In order to preserve Epoch 1 schedule and avoid additional
 costs, the Program Executive Officer (PEO) approved the transition of the space segment development to a single vendor as of September 2024.

 Space Systems Command, Space Development Agency, and the Missile Defense Agency will continue to use the Combined Program Office construct to develop and
 implement a system-of-systems integration strategy across for Missile Warning and Tracking and Missile Defense constellations supporting Low Earth Orbit, Medium
 Earth Orbit, Geosynchronous Orbit and Polar Orbit regimes. Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking Medium Earth Orbit Epoch 1 is now comprised of a single space
 vendor and multiple ground lines of effort to include the following:
 -Space vehicle development efforts are currently underway with Millennium Space Systems for the delivery of twelve space vehicles.
 -Delivery includes: design, build, hardware integration, testing, delivery, launch vehicle integration, space vehicle.
 -Launch & early orbit operations, calibration, tuning, flying, and delivery of formatted two-dimensional tracks into the Real-Time Transfer Service for incorporation with
 other sensors data necessary for warning/tracking requirements and operations.
 -Mission Data Processing and unique ground software on contract as of December 2022.
 -Perform the integration of the space vehicles into the operations center for command and control at the Boulder Ground Innovation Facility (BGIF).
 -Develop integration command and control and Mission Data Processing software to operate constellation of Medium Earth Orbit space vehicles for supporting multiple
 collection layers.
 -Additional ground applications for ground resource management and sensor tasking will be included as part of the Operations and Integration contract and transition to
 the Ground Management and Integration contract in support of all Epochs.
 -Acquire, build, install, test, and operate ground-based antennas for uplink/downlink of commands and mission data. At least two sites and six apertures are required for
 Epoch 1. The antennas for Epoch 1 are on contract as of December 2022 and will be located at Schriever Space Force Base, Colorado, and Al Udeid Air Base, Qatar.
 An additional set of antennas at Clear Space Force Station, Alaska will be modified to support Epoch 1 ground contacts. Additional overseas locations are necessary to
 ensure Ground Entry Point (GEP) availability for future Epochs and will improve communication diversity, and mission assurance.
 -Test, assess, and validate sensor performance on the ground and on-orbit to ensure track data is integrated by Program of Record data and fusion operational
 programs such as Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) (PE 1206440SF), Ballistic Missile Defense Overhead Persistent Infrared Architecture
 (BOA), other classified partners and missions, research and development multi-intelligence fusion (PE 1206442SF), and intelligence characterization. Space vehicle
 testing is on contract as of December 2022. Fusion software studies underway with FORGE program as of March 2023, and with BOA as of 2024.
 -Mature integrated digital model: support Space System Command's role as the mission area integrator, perform resiliency analyses, baseline future requirements, and
 assess performance against current and new targets. On contract as of May 2021.

 The Epoch 2 acquisition began in FY 2025 and will continue in FY 2027 with the acquisition of additional planes of missile warning and tracking space vehicle capability
 (total number of space vehicles depend on source selection); managing up to two prime vendors delivering space vehicles as well as Ground Command and Control and
 Mission Data Processing software. The program will leverage the FORGE framework and BGIF for both operations and underlying hardware and software framework
 services and will continue the tasking and fusion architecture that began in Epoch 1 for Epoch 2 acquisitions. Furthermore, Epoch 2 will continue to manage a ground

 management & integration contractor to assist with on boarding space craft and vendor operations into the BGIF. Epoch 2 will expand upon the current GEPs to procure
 additional antennas necessary to support space vehicle planes. Finally, Epoch 2 will also continue the use of model-based systems engineering and digital models to
 ease integration.

 This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver Missile Warning and Tracking capability. The use of such
 program funds would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 1206392SF and 1206398SF.

 This program is in Budget Activity 5, System Development and Demonstration (SDD) because it has passed Milestone B approval and is conducting engineering and
 manufacturing development tasks aimed at meeting validated requirements prior to full rate production.$$, $$The program office is developing and prototyping the Resilient Missile Warning Tracking (MWT) MEO (Project 657MEO) for Guardians across Missile Warning and
Missile Tracking (MW/MT) mission area. As a result, the Service will advance space-based technology associated with Golden Dome, and deter, neutralize, defeat and/
or destroy counterspace threats and defend the homeland.

 A new class of threat requires a new class of architecture. Since legacy systems alone cannot maintain custody of advanced, dim and maneuverable missile threats,
 Resilient MWT delivers a multi-orbit architecture designed to defeat new threats, support homeland defense, Combatant Command operations and the broader missile
 defense kill chain. The United States Space Force Space Systems Command and Space Development Agency are collaborating to deliver Overhead Persistent
 Infrared capabilities, in concert with Department of War and Intelligence Community partners, to support a proliferated space architecture that is resilient by design and
 capable of operating through contested environments. Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking - Medium Earth Orbit space and ground efforts pivot the Department
 of the Air Force's legacy missile warning force design to a more resilient multi-orbit approach to counter advanced missiles, hypersonic glide vehicles, and fractional
 orbital bombardment threats. Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking Medium Earth Orbit was originally anchored in Missile Warning and Missile Defense Capability
 Development Document requirements validated by the Joint Requirements Oversight Council; there is now a Joint Requirement Oversight Council-approved Capability
 Development Document Annex with very specific Medium Earth Orbit and Low Earth Orbit requirements. Constellation resiliency is foundational to the Department of the
 Air Force's Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking force design, therefore, the Overhead Persistent Infrared Family of Systems, including Missile Warning and Tracking
 Medium Earth Orbit, is designed to work cohesively to gain and maintain custody of a spectrum of missile threats.

 This program falls within the Missile Warning and Missile Tracking (MW/MT) mission area which provides the multi-orbit space and ground architecture required to detect
 and track missiles and hypersonic glide vehicles worldwide. Space Force investment program interdependencies include:
 RDT&E Budget Line Items: Missile Defense Radars (1203873SF); Ballistic Missile EW Systems (1203909SF); Joint Tactical Ground System (1208053SF); NCMC - TW/
 AA System (1203906SF); Next - Generation OPIR (1206442SF); Next - Generation - GEO (1206443SF); Next - Generation - Ground (1206440SF); Next - Generation
 - Polar (1206444SF); NUDET Detection System (1203913SF); Resilient MW / MT - LEO (1206446SF); Resilient MW / MT - MEO (1206447SF) and elements of
 Procurement Budget Line Item: Space Mods (SPCMOD).

