C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                               FY 2025      FY 2026      FY 2027
Title: Missile Warning and Tracking - MEO Epoch 1                                                                                   458.860      207.212      259.203

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                       FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Description: This activity funds development of Medium Earth Orbit space vehicles, with two launches planned to deliver twelve
space vehicles by FY 2028, and ground efforts with operations necessary to deliver initial capability for the combined Low Earth
Orbit and Medium Earth Orbit architecture. Initial capability consists of regional tracking, mission management and control, and
coordinated regional warning and tracking access validated through on-orbit measurements. After performance validation is
complete, prototype sensors will feed data directly to operational warning and defense systems. Furthermore, the initial capability
will provide sensitivity to detect emerging threats, accurate tracking to contain maneuvering targets, and mission data delivery
within required latency timelines to close the kill-chain. Initial Warfighter Capability is now defined in the Overhead Persistent
Infrared Resilient Medium Earth Orbit/Low Earth Orbit Capability Development Document Annex as global missile tracking access
and will be provided in Epoch 2.

Data Fusion: Test, assess, and validate sensor performance on the ground and on-orbit to ensure track data is integrated by
program of record data fusion operational programs such as Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) (PE
1206440SF), Ballistic Missile Defense Overhead Persistent Infrared Architecture (BOA), other classified partners and missions,
research and development multi-intelligence fusion (PE 1206442SF), and intelligence characterization. Space Vehicle testing
is on contract as of December 2022. Fusion software studies underway with Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution
(FORGE) program as of March 2023. Additional early integration support and studies with BOA started in FY 2024. In FY 2025,
sensor models began to support future modeling and simulation activities with the Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution
(FORGE) and Missile Defense program offices.

FY 2026 Plans:
Space: Crucial deliveries of payloads and satellite buses from the remaining contractor for integration and assembly. The vendor
intends to deliver flight payloads and satellite buses for the first six satellites and begin space vehicle level assembly, integration
and testing. Millennium Space Systems will initiate assembling and testing space vehicles 7-12 to complete two orbital planes of
capability. They will complete launch vehicle integration studies and launch vehicle selection for both launches, and support first
launch no earlier than the end of 3Q FY 2027.

Ground: Contractor will complete software builds for both command and control and mission data processing; The MEO Space
Operations Center (MSOC) fit up at the Boulder Ground Innovation Facility (BGIF) will be completed and the operations floor
will be prepared for launch rehearsals. The Ground Entry Point (GEP) contractor will complete Integration, test, validation, and
verification in preparation for launch rehearsals and Launch and Early On-Orbit Test campaign. Ground antenna initialization and
system end to end testing at the BGIF, Schriever Space Force Base, Al Udeid Air Base, Clear Space Force Station, and other
associated antennas will be completed in FY 2026.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Data Fusion: Finalize verification and validation campaigns to ensure the fidelity of the models are adequate to be integrated into
enterprise sensor test campaigns spanning the entire Overhead Persistent Infrared architecture. In FY 2026, major simulation and
ground test campaign planning will occur to ensure sensor models and live on-orbit data will be ingested at the appropriate missile
warning and missile defense test events occurring in FY 2026-2027. Work with data fusion programs (FORGE, BOA, Persistent
Unified Messaging Architecture) to ensure on-orbit data is timely and accurate.
FY 2027 Plans:
Space: Final testing and integration of flight payloads and satellite buses for Plane 1. These events will culminate in satellite
shipment to launch site at Cape Canaveral and initial launch capability. Immediately following launch, Millennium Space Systems
will conduct early orbit checkout and testing procedures. The vendor will then conduct operational testing of the full orbital plane
of satellites. In addition, Epoch 1 will be going through assembly, integration and testing of Plane 2 in preparation for a second
launch and on-orbit test campaign beginning in mid to late FY 2028.

Ground: Conduct site configuration and instrumentation efforts, including RF interference testing, installation of hardware, system
integration, and execute engineering support during developmental testing and implement corrective actions, through the use of
a deficiency reporting list, resulting from developmental testing at GEP sites at Schriever Space Force Base, Al Udeid Air Base,
and Clear Space Force Station, as well as the MEO Space Operations Center (MSOC) located at the Boulder Ground Innovation
Facility (BGIF).
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 increase due to continuing execution of MEO Epoch 1 testing and integration of flight payloads and satellite buses and
start maintenance of Ground Entry Point (GEP) sites.
Title: Resilient Missile Warning / Missile Tracking - MEO Epoch 2                                                                        297.489     468.636      1,154.459
Description: This activity funds development of Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking Medium Earth Orbit Epoch 2 space
vehicles, up to four launches planned to deliver up to four planes of capability (10-22 space vehicles) by FY 2031 and supporting
ground efforts with operations necessary to deliver Initial Warfighter Capability (IWC) for Medium Earth Orbit architecture. Epoch
2 builds upon Epoch 1 to meet JROC-validated Capability Development Document requirements through agile development.
The Epoch 2 acquisition will balance delivery of the IWC while establishing a path toward delivering Full Warfighter Capability
(FWC) in future Epochs. The Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking Medium Earth Orbit Epoch 2 prototyping effort will deliver
a new post-boost phase, global missile tracking access capability, and enhanced raid coverage mission capability to contain
dimmer and maneuvering hypersonic and ballistic missiles with unpredictable trajectories. This effort will demonstrate the ability to
function within a coordinated Overhead Persistent Infrared enterprise, which receives taskings from the Joint Overhead Persistent
Infrared Planning Center, executes that tasking through sensor collections and delivers missile data back to the enterprise. All
space vehicles will operate in an integrated fashion through a common ground system rooted in the Future Operationally Resilient

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Ground Evolution (FORGE) framework. Epoch 2 space vehicle design, build, integration and test efforts began in FY 2025. This
effort also funds mission data processing, command and control, ground operations, ground entry points and system engineering,
terrestrial communications, integration, test and demonstration efforts with stakeholders and mission partners.

FY 2026 Plans:
Space: Continue Epoch 2 activities to include managing multiple contracts executing space system development, ground
segment development, and integration at our operating center. Will consist of preliminary and critical design reviews that finalize
the designs. Primes will transition from design to build of space vehicles and ground development. Epoch 2 will build out the
architecture for global missile tracking with up to four planes of additional capability.

Ground: Begin site surveys and selection process for additional GEP locations needed for Epoch 2. Initiate and award Ground
Management and Integration contract to add Epoch 2 capability to the MSOC, to build a Backup MSOC, and to build additional
GEPs. Start design of Epoch 2 MSOC fit up for additional space vehicle provider operations at BGIF, design of Backup MSOC, &
additional GEPs.

Funds allow both space and ground efforts to rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness
necessary to operate in the contested space domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies,
technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government
partnership, and international opportunities to respond to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.
FY 2027 Plans:
Space: Continue Epoch 2 activities to finalize Critical Design Review (4Q FY 2026) for two planes of capability consisting of
ten missile warning & tracking space vehicles. The vendor will execute Payload Integration and Test; Bus Material Readiness
Review; Bus Test Readiness Review; Bus Integration and Test; Ground Software Demos (for Ground Segment Integration);
conduct Mission Systems Engineering Integration and Test activities; and develop procedures for the Launch Early Operations
and Test campaign. Epoch 2 Planes 1 and 2 will be prepared for staggered Pre-Ship Reviews and deliveries to the launch site in
2Q FY 2029 and 4Q FY 2029. The program office will be executing source selection activities for a second Other Transaction for
Prototype Agreement award for a third plane of Epoch 2 capability comprised of three to six additional missile warning & tracking
satellite vehicles. Award is anticipated no earlier than 1QFY27. The Epoch 2 Vendor 2 will finalize System Readiness Review and
Preliminary Design Review for up to two additional planes of capability (space vehicle quantity TBD). Epoch 2 Vendor 2 will work
towards a critical design review in FY 2028.

Ground: The ground infrastructure will support two planes in development and continue to expand to support a full four plane
architecture. The mission data processing application development, command and control software, and facilities build will

