 2033. FY 2026 funding supports final build, test, and delivery of flight payloads and buses to support Epoch 1, space vehicle level assembly integration and test, and
 launch/early orbit operations. FY 2026 funding also includes ground activities previously captured in PE 1206448SF, Project 657124, that continue ground segment
 Mission Data Processing application development and integration, command and control software and facilities build and integration into the Medium Earth Orbit Space
 Operations Center, and ground entry point site construction to support on-orbit initialization in FY 2027. In order to preserve Epoch 1 schedule and avoid additional
 costs, the Program Executive Officer (PEO) approved the transition of the space segment development to a single vendor as of September 2024.

 Space Systems Command, Space Development Agency, and the Missile Defense Agency will continue to use the Combined Program Office construct to develop and
 implement a system-of-systems integration strategy across for Missile Warning and Tracking and Missile Defense constellations supporting Low Earth Orbit, Medium
 Earth Orbit, Geosynchronous Orbit and Polar Orbit regimes. Resilient Missile Warning and Tracking Medium Earth Orbit Epoch 1 is now comprised of a single space
 vendor and multiple ground lines of effort to include the following:
 -Space vehicle development efforts are currently underway with Millennium Space Systems for the delivery of twelve space vehicles.
 -Delivery includes: design, build, hardware integration, testing, delivery, launch vehicle integration, space vehicle.
 -Launch & early orbit operations, calibration, tuning, flying, and delivery of formatted two-dimensional tracks into the Real-Time Transfer Service for incorporation with
 other sensors data necessary for warning/tracking requirements and operations.
 -Mission Data Processing and unique ground software on contract as of December 2022.
 -Perform the integration of the space vehicles into the operations center for command and control at the Boulder Ground Innovation Facility (BGIF).
 -Develop integration command and control and Mission Data Processing software to operate constellation of Medium Earth Orbit space vehicles for supporting multiple
 collection layers.
 -Additional ground applications for ground resource management and sensor tasking will be included as part of the Operations and Integration contract and transition to
 the Ground Management and Integration contract in support of all Epochs.
 -Acquire, build, install, test, and operate ground-based antennas for uplink/downlink of commands and mission data. At least two sites and six apertures are required for
 Epoch 1. The antennas for Epoch 1 are on contract as of December 2022 and will be located at Schriever Space Force Base, Colorado, and Al Udeid Air Base, Qatar.
 An additional set of antennas at Clear Space Force Station, Alaska will be modified to support Epoch 1 ground contacts. Additional overseas locations are necessary to
 ensure Ground Entry Point (GEP) availability for future Epochs and will improve communication diversity, and mission assurance.
 -Test, assess, and validate sensor performance on the ground and on-orbit to ensure track data is integrated by Program of Record data and fusion operational
 programs such as Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) (PE 1206440SF), Ballistic Missile Defense Overhead Persistent Infrared Architecture
 (BOA), other classified partners and missions, research and development multi-intelligence fusion (PE 1206442SF), and intelligence characterization. Space vehicle
 testing is on contract as of December 2022. Fusion software studies underway with FORGE program as of March 2023, and with BOA as of 2024.
 -Mature integrated digital model: support Space System Command's role as the mission area integrator, perform resiliency analyses, baseline future requirements, and
 assess performance against current and new targets. On contract as of May 2021.

