test, and field software/hardware from various programs (product lines) leveraging the scheduled release cadence for capabilities
as they mature.

FY 2026 Plans:
Continue technology maturation, development and risk reduction projects in support of various F-22 development efforts.
Examples include, but are not limited to, continued development of high-bandwidth beyond-line-of-sight satellite communications,
assessments of emerging systems and tactics development, and system hardware development and testing. Project Geyser+
continued flight demonstrations to support technology maturation and continued hardware design analysis to inform production
configuration and integration requirements for Engineering and Manufacturing Development (EMD).
FY 2027 Plans:
Complete development of high-bandwidth beyond-line-of-sight demonstration satellite communications capabilities. Continue
annual, on-going, technology maturation, development and risk reduction projects in support of various F-22 development efforts.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Increase of $5.537 million from FY2026 to FY2027 reflects the increase of high-bandwidth beyond-line-of-sight demonstration
satellite communications capabilities work, and furthering technology maturation testing activity.
Title: Sensor Systems                                                                                                                  129.486     103.552        106.712
Description: Sensor Systems improves sensor capabilities to maintain air superiority and preserve first look, first shot, and first
kill capability. This includes developing and maturing advanced sensor capabilities.

Starting in the 27 PB, Operational Flight Program (OFP) software was transitioned to the Software Pathway for Enabling
Expedited Deliveries (SPEED) major thrust for FY2026 and FY2027.

FY 2026 Plans:
Continue Sensor Enhancements software and hardware integration. Receive Developmental Test/Operational Test (DT/OT)
assets, begin flight test on F-22's flying test bed in 3QFY2026, and begin DT/OT flight test on the F-22 in 4QFY2026. Continue
technology maturation and complete the manufacturing readiness assessment.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue Sensor DT/OT flight test. Receive remaining DT/OT test assets and support equipment for use during testing to inform
maintenance planning and logistic support. DT/OT testing expected to complete and support a Release 6 fielding decision in
4QFY2027. Complete transition of remaining manufacturing activities from the EMD facilities to the production facilities.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:

Operational Systems Development

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Increase of $3.160 million from FY2026 to FY2027 reflects continued development and integration as Developmental Test/
Operational Test (DT/OT) flight test activities continue through FY2027.
Title: Controlled Reception Pattern Antenna (CRPA)/Anti-Jam Global Positioning System (GPS) Antenna                                  19.816       3.445          2.347
Description: In accordance with Capability Development Guidance Memorandum (CDGM) 09-22-03 for Resilient Position,
Navigation, and Timing (PNT), the Controlled Reception Pattern Antenna (CRPA) product line will replace the F-22's legacy Fixed
Reception Pattern Array (FRPA) antenna. CRPA/Anti-Jam Global Positioning System (GPS) Antenna provides advanced antenna
technologies which will dramatically reduce an adversary's ability to jam or otherwise interfere with GPS signals.

Starting in the 27 PB, Operational Flight Program (OFP) software was transitioned to the Software Pathway for Enabling
Expedited Deliveries (SPEED) major thrust for FY2026 and FY2027.

FY 2026 Plans:
Hardware corrective action effort is being worked to mitigate service life issues with a projected completion date of July 2026.
Complete corrective action and service life retest in 4QFY2026. Research, Test, and mature alternate GPS Anti-Jam solutions.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue the development and procurement of integration hardware for Anti-Jam GPS solutions.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Decrease of $1.098 million from FY2026 to FY2027 is attributable to the program's reduction in Engineering and Manufacturing
Development (EMD) activities in preparation for procurement efforts.
Title: Embedded GPS/Inertial Navigation System (INS) Modernization (EGI-M)                                                            2.850       2.680          6.792
Description: In compliance with M-Code Mandate Public Law 111-383, EGI-M will provide an M-Code compliant, anti-spoofing
PNT solution to prevent exploitation of the weapon system by adversaries, enable more accurate tracking of GPS satellites, and
support a more secure and flexible cryptography architecture.

This effort covers the M-Code Weapons product line and EGI-M integration, test, software, and hardware necessary to ensure the
F-22's ability to employ M-Code configured weapons and field the EGI-M. The Air Force Weapons Program Office is scheduled to
field M-Code- enabled weapons prior to the availability of an M-Code GPS solution for the F-22.

Starting in the 27 PB, Operational Flight Program (OFP) software was transitioned to the SPEED major thrust for FY2026 and
FY2027.

FY 2026 Plans:

Operational Systems Development

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
F-22 will begin aircraft and Flying Test Bed (FTB) Group A design efforts to support Embedded Global Positioning System (GPS)/
Inertial Navigation System (INS) Modernization (EGI-M) integration. F-22 will start integrating EGI-M Engineering Development
Models (EDM) into the Vehicle System Simulator (VSS).
FY 2027 Plans:
F-22 will begin heads up display/integrated control panel (HUD/ICP) Software Development, begin Aircraft Group A engineering
for Developmental Test (DT) / Occupational Test (OT) aircraft, and begin integrating hardware into the FTB. Hardware integration
Vehicle System Simulator (VSS) will complete prior to starting the Agile Integration Laboratory (AIL) and Ogden Test Enterprise
(OTE) integration in FY2028.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Increase of $4.112 million from FY2026 to FY2027 is attributable to the ramp up of efforts in accordance with planned Engineering
and Manufacturing Development (EMD) activities.
Title: Link 16 (L16) and Open System Architecture (OSA) Increment II Improvements                                                     74.420       0.000          0.000
Description: Develop, enhance, and field Link-16, Open System Architecture (OSA), and Multifunction Information Distribution
System Joint Tactical Radio System (MIDS JTRS) hardware/software/firmware capabilities to enable tactical data sharing between
5th generation and 4th generation aircraft. The OSA implementation provides a pathway to a more competitive and open F-22
modernization that will provide infrastructure enhancements to enable future combat capabilities.

In FY2026, Link-16 transitioned to the Software Pathway for Enabling Expedited Deliveries (SPEED) major thrust. Development
and integration activities related to Link-16 are ongoing and documented under the SPEED major thrust.

FY 2026 Plans:
FY2026 plans are documented in the F-22 SPEED major thrust.
FY 2027 Plans:
FY2027 plans are documented in the F-22 SPEED major thrust.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Documented in the F-22 SPEED major thrust.
Title: Mode 5 Identify Friend or Foe Challenge (IFFC)                                                                                 45.105      10.251          9.240
Description: Mode 5 IFFC is a Joint Requirements Oversight Council-mandated Blue Force identification capability that improves
Raptor survivability, reduces fratricide risk Department of War wide, and the Mode 5 IFFC capability incorporates new and
updated hardware and software to add a new waveform, new cryptography, and additional data.

Operational Systems Development

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Starting in the 27 PB, Operational Flight Program (OFP) software was transitioned to the Software Pathway for Enabling
Expedited Deliveries (SPEED) major thrust for FY2026 and FY2027.

FY 2026 Plans:
Finalize software development, integration, and lab testing of select Mode 5 classified enabler capabilities. Complete integration
and validation activities of Mode 5 Identify Friend or Foe Challenge (IFFC) circuit cards and crypto cards hardware. Complete
hardware modification and integration activities on test aircraft. Continue Mode 5 IFFC flight testing activities in conjunction with
Raptor Operational Flight Program flight testing. Continue spectrum certification activities to obtain a Stage 4 (operational) Radio
Frequency Authorization (RFA) for Mode 5 Identify Friend or Foe (IFF) operations on Combat Air Forces (CAF) aircraft.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue Mode 5 IFFC flight testing activities in conjunction with Raptor OFP. Continue spectrum certification activities to
obtain a Stage 4 (operational) RFA for Mode 5 IFF operations on CAF aircraft. Perform hardware support activities to include
troubleshooting and defect resolution as needed in conjunction with Release 6 fielding.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Decrease of $1.011 million from FY2026 to FY2027 is due to decreased Engineering and Manufacturing Development (EMD)
requirements in FY2027.
Title: Low Drag Tanks and Pylons (LDTP)                                                                                                   74.666      54.976         33.980
Description: The F-22 Low Drag Tanks and Pylons (LDTP) are advanced technological designs providing increased persistence
and range while maintaining lethality and survivability. The low drag tanks are intended to minimally increase drag for external
tank carriage, facilitate supersonic flight with external tanks and extend the range of the F-22. The pylons are equipped with smart
rack pneumatic technology to accurately control ejection performance and minimize drag without stores.

LDTP risk reduction activities were captured under the Advanced Technology Development (ATD) major thrust. Documentation of
the development and integration components as part of the EMD program is captured under the LDTP major thrust.

Starting in the 27 PB, OFP software was transitioned to the SPEED major thrust for FY2026 and FY2027.

