Title: Cryptographic Modernization                                                                                                  0.000      16.295         49.018
Description: The Cryptographic Modernization program will update F-22 radios with revised interoperability and cryptographic
security requirements as mandated by the Second-Generation Anti-Jam Tactical ultra-high frequency (UHF) Radio for North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) (SATURN), U.S. Procurement Specification SS103118. This major thrust also covers
F-22 program activities required to update Tactical Secure Voice Cryptographic Interoperability Specification (TSVCIS) 2.1 to
version 3.1.1, a key component of Cryptographic Modernization Planning as directed by Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff
Instruction-6510.02D and in accordance with guidance from the National Cryptographic Solution Management Office (NSCMO),
dated August 2020.

Starting in the 27 PB, Operational Flight Program (OFP) software was transitioned to the Software Pathway for Enabling
Expedited Deliveries (SPEED) major thrust for FY2026 and FY2027.

FY 2026 Plans:
FY2026 efforts will include the commencement and ramp up into Engineering and Manufacturing Development (EMD) program
activities for the SATURN and TSVCIS solutions. These efforts include the development of new Communication, Navigation,
and Identification (CNI) modules and new KOV-28A cryptographic module to enable it to handle the increased processing power
required with the implementation of the full National Security Agency (NSA) mandates. Work also includes the consolidation of
the current CNI rack to provide growth space for current and future communication and cryptographic upgrades such as, but
not limited to Open Radio Architecture (ORA) Provisioning. SATURN / TSVCIS will continue working with the NSA to ensure
certification requirements are met.
FY 2027 Plans:
FY2027 efforts will include further development of hardware for the cryptographic modernization program. As the SATURN,
TSVCIS, and ORA provisioning work continues to mature, module level testing for the hardware will begin. As the development of
the KOV-28A crypto progresses, coordination with the NSA on cryptographic certification will continue.
