E. Acquisition Strategy
The F-22 utilized Sec 804 Middle Tier of Acquisition (MTA) to rapidly develop and field advanced capability. Development efforts were conducted under a Rapid
Prototyping MTA, which concluded at the end of FY2023 with the exception of the Sensor Enhancements program, which received a 10-month extension to enable
the completion of a technical demonstration on the F-22. In 4QFY2024, the Sensor Enhancements program transitioned to a Rapid Fielding MTA authority (8 Aug
2024) and placed the initial Group B kit production order (29 Aug 2024). A second Group B kit production order was placed on 4 Apr 2025. The following programs are
now executing/transitioning to Major Capability Acquisition (MCA) programs: Mode 5 Identify Friend or Foe - Challenge (IFFC), Controlled Reception Pattern Antenna
(CRPA)/Anti-Jam Global Positioning System (GPS) Antenna, Embedded Global Positioning System (GPS)/ Inertial Navigation System (INS) - Modernized (EGI- M), Low
Drag Tanks and Pylons (LDTP), Infrared Defense Suite (IRDS), Geyser+, Cryptographic Modernization, and Hybrid Satellite Communications (SATCOM). In FY2026, all
OFP capabilities along with two MCA programs, Link 16 and Open System Architecture (OSA) Improvements and Helmet Mounted Display Cueing System (HMDCS),
were transitioned to the F-22 Software Pathway for Enabling Expedited Deliveries (SPEED) Software Acquisition Pathway program. SPEED is separately identified as
a major thrust starting in the FY2027 PB. The programs will use the established Indefinite Delivery Indefinite Quantity (IDIQ) contract vehicles to maximize flexibility
to start, stop, accelerate, and decelerate projects to maximize F-22 capabilities given the changing threat environment. In conjunction with the Raptor Enhancement
Development & Integration II (REDI II) IDIQ ordering contract, the new Advanced Raptor Enhancement and Sustainment (ARES) IDIQ is a follow-on contract that began
taking orders in FY2022.




