INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0603382N$$, 2027, $$Project 0303: Tactical Advancements for the Next Generation (TANG) is a Navy-wide innovation project that has expanded throughout the Department of War (DoW)
that addresses mission-driven, human-centered challenges for warfighters and developers. TANG drives front-end innovation for national security utilizing emerging
technologies including Extended Reality (XR) and Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning (AI/ML). TANG solves these challenges leveraging a divergent-convergent
process (e.g., design thinking) and harnessing the expertise and perspective of the user, subject matter experts (SMEs), stakeholders, and industry partners, to ideate
and create new actionable solutions that will impact the DoW. For each project, TANG will tailor the methods and approaches to the respective topic and scope.
Approaches include domain user research, facilitation of workshops, strategic process improvements, building project roadmaps, and rapid prototyping of perspective
solutions.

Project Unit 0304: Technology Maturation and Transition: Funds vetted and endorsed prototype technologies and capabilities based on projects curated by N94 from
initiatives throughout the joint and USN innovation portfolio. Projects align with National Defense Strategy (NDS), Chief of Naval Operations (CAAPP) and Fleet priorities
and receive USN endorsement based on a rigorous vetting process and the closure of critical capability gaps. Projects are cross-domain and accelerate integration
of high priority technologies to enable transition into Programs of Record and support warfighter needs. Projects also support USN experimentation in priority areas
required for evaluation and transition of key technologies.

Project Unit 0324: This funding supports the implementation of the Naval Open Systems Architecture (OSA) Strategy. The Navy's implementation of OSA and similar
constructs like Modular Open Systems Approaches (MOSA). The OSA transformation effort will be applied to programs of record. Those elements include ensuring that
naval systems, families of systems, programs, and prototypes move to MOSA in accordance with DoW Memo 7 Nov 2025, Joint Memo 17 Dec 2024, 10 USC 4402 5
Nov 2025, and SECNAV Instruction 5000.2G (Department of the Navy Implementation of the Defense Acquisition System, 08 April 2022) which mandates that all DoW
programs utilize MOSA to field affordable and interoperable systems. This project facilitates a strategic shift to digitally engineered modular systems deployment. This
improves innovation and economies of scale throughout the Navy and Marine Corps. This project includes identification of use cases and cost avoidance the benefits
 as a result of moving the Navy towards an open systems approach, supported by the development of open systems technologies and integrated best operational and
 technical practices for open systems development within Naval acquisition. Naval MOSA ensures system architectures become extensible and scalable in function,
 capacity, and workload to meet Service and Joint warfighting requirements. This also includes the identification and development of common software components,
 functions, reuse methodologies, and extensible product lines. Open architectures set the standard for technology fields to promote interoperability. The Advanced
 Combat System Technology line advances the principles of modular design and design disclosure, reusable application software, interoperability and secure information
 exchange, lifecycle affordability and encouraging standardization.

The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Research, Development, Test and Evaluation, Navy includes $19,307 thousand of discretionary and $39,000 thousand of
