$$, $$45a3d6cde8dbabf149a2a394a12421d310094c9147acc21d21981a427b75a62d$$, $${"A": "f6708f2e4351d544230fb94ad15e64b1a7d89119cd5f53641ae627d83329b4b5", "D": "9cf27396f64917421bdb61be25062fb2d0a5b672f74ce388c5e6fdebe339acf5", "E": "70f912d7fc00b56b091719c0a9f5ce9d4a0a1b2bcd5f59bb1d307d6d6ebab646"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Air Force/FY27 Air Force Research, Development, Test & Evaluation  Volume IV.pdf$$, 199, $$2026-05-07T23:10:02.989896+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0207590F$$, 2027, $$The Air Force SEEK EAGLE Office (AFSEO) is designated by the Assistant Secretary of the Air Force (Acquisition, Technology, and Logistics) as the center of expertise
for aircraft-store compatibility activities and as the primary source of technical analysis and test support, as well as the central data repository, for the SEEK EAGLE
process. The SEEK EAGLE process is a rigorous analysis of many factors to assure the safe and acceptable carriage and release (employment and jettison), safe
escape, and ballistics accuracy of all stores on Air Force and foreign military sales aircraft. Thus, the AFSEO's mission as an accelerator is to ensure that every aircraft
type is capable of employing the weapons and stores needed to meet Combatant Commander requirements, directly supporting the Secretary of the Air Force's
(SECAF) and Secretary of War (SECWAR) operational and acquisition priorities.

The Air Force operates a variety of combat and other aircraft that carry numerous and varied stores: bombs, missiles, rockets, palletized munitions, chaff/flare, fuel
tanks, cargo pods, targeting pods, electronic countermeasures pods, etc. Stores are carried in many different loading combinations determined by operational and
training scenarios, missions, tactics, and weapon development programs. Additionally, aircraft-store configuration (carriage and employment) requirements change as
operational plans and tactics are updated and/or as new stores are developed and fielded. Aircraft program managers must provide SEEK EAGLE certifications for all
aircraft-store configurations within their user-established carriage and employment parameters before they may be used for operations, test, or training. The AFSEO
completes flight clearance and certification recommendations through any combination of engineering analysis, wind tunnel testing, modeling and simulation, and
ground/flight test and evaluation. These AFSEO recommendations are key artifacts for aircraft program managers demonstrating MIL-STD compliance for airworthiness
and safety. AFSEO's efforts within the SEEK EAGLE process primarily encompass these eight engineering disciplines: Fit and Function, Flutter, Aircraft and Store
Structural Integrity, Stability and Control, Electromagnetic Compatibility/Interference (EMC/EMI), Separations, Ballistics, and Safe Escape.

In support of certification, the AFSEO recommends approximately 1000 aircraft-store combinations for flight each year through engineering analysis and testing. The
AFSEO certification portfolio includes the Next Generation Air Dominance (NGAD) Family of Systems, Collaborative Combat Aircraft (CCA) and B-21, as well as the
following Mission Design Series aircraft: B-1, B-2, B-52, F-15, F-16, QF-16, F-22, F-35, KC-135, C-130, C-17, HH-60, MH-139, MQ-9, OA-1k, T-7, AT-6, and more.
Accounting for factors from aircraft dynamics to day-of-flight conditions, AFSEO develops sophisticated Safe Escape and Ballistics tools that are integrated into the Joint
Mission Planning System (JMPS). AFSEO also provides specialized software like Combat Weapon Delivery Software (CWDS) and Guided Weapon Trajectory Software
(GWTS) directly to specific users, including approximately 25 FMS customers FMS customers. The SEEK EAGLE Office also works in coordination with the
Air Force Safety Center to provide Hazards of Electromagnetic Radiation to Ordnance (HERO) analysis and certification recommendations for ordnance systems
containing electro-explosive devices. Additionally, to accelerate certification timelines and ensure a sustainable Air Force aircraft-store capability, AFSEO actively
integrates cutting-edge technologies into the SEEK EAGLE process, streamlining the path to rapid acquisition and deployment.

Operational Systems Development

SEEK EAGLE funds are budgeted to support certification testing and analysis for a variety of new and inventory stores, including a growing focus on Advanced Precision
Kill Weapon System (APKWS) rockets used for Counter-UAS, as well as Family of Affordable Mass Missiles (FAMM), specifically the -L (lugged) and -P (palletized)
variants, Small Diameter Bombs (SDB I and II), Joint Direct Attack Munition (JDAM) variants, Quickstrike mines, Joint Air-to-Surface Standoff Missile (JASSM), Long-
Range Anti-Ship Missile (LRASM), Air-to-Air Missiles (AIM-120 and AIM-9X), Miniature Air-Launched Decoy (MALD), smart bomb racks, targeting pods with video data
link capabilities, the B61-12 nuclear free-fall weapon, penetrator warhead upgrades, electronic warfare and reconnaissance pods, and instrumentation pods. SEEK
EAGLE funds also support certification of other inventory stores on Combat Air Forces (CAF) and Special Operations Command (SOCOM) aircraft. To ensure that these
certification efforts are as cost-effective and efficient as possible, the AFSEO maintains the central data archive for all aircraft store compatibility analyses; while this
archive requires ongoing investment in hardware, software, and licensing, it drastically reduces the need for costly and time-consuming ground and flight re-testing and
speeds up acquisition and development by providing critical data, lessons learned, and reduced analysis time to other Department of Defense (DoD) organizations.
In addition, these funds further support capability development and weapons certification efforts required by Air Combat Command (ACC) to achieve Full Operational
Capability (FOC) for the F-35A. These weapons certification efforts directly support SECAF emphasis areas (NGAD, B-21 and F-47 Families of Systems) and SECWAR
emphasis areas (Nuclear Modernization, CCAs, Counter-small UAS Initiatives, and Munitions).

This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such programs
funds would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program element 0605827F, 0605828F, 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605832F, 0605833F, 0605898F,
0606398F. In FY 2025, 8.925M was expended for civilian pay expenses in this program element, and 11.550M is forecasted for civilian pay expenses in FY 2026 in this
program element.

This program is in Budget Activity 7, Operational System Development because this budget activity includes development efforts to upgrade systems that have been
fielded or have received approval for full rate production and anticipate production funding in the current or subsequent fiscal year.$$, $$The Air Force SEEK EAGLE Office (AFSEO) is designated by the Assistant Secretary of the Air Force (Acquisition, Technology, and Logistics) as the center of expertise
